1611kjv#2 Esdras 7:47,56
[47]For what profit is it for men now in this present time to live in heaviness, and after death to look for punishment?
[56]For while we lived and committed iniquity, we considered not that we should begin to suffer for it after death.

#2 Esdras 9:1-12
[1]He answered me then, and said, Measure thou the time diligently in itself: and when thou seest part of the signs past, which I have told thee before,
[2]Then shalt thou understand, that it is the very same time, wherein the Highest will begin to visit the world which he made.
[3]Therefore when there shall be seen earthquakes and uproars of the people in the world:
[4]Then shalt thou well understand, that the most High spake of those things from the days that were before thee, even from the beginning.
[5]For like as all that is made in the world hath a beginning and an end, and the end is manifest:
[6]Even so the times also of the Highest have plain beginnings in wonder and powerful works, and endings in effects and signs.
[7]And every one that shall be saved, and shall be able to escape by his works, and by faith, whereby ye have believed,
[8]Shall be preserved from the said perils, and shall see my salvation in my land, and within my borders: for I have sanctified them for me from the beginning.
[9]Then shall they be in pitiful case, which now have abused my ways: and they that have cast them away despitefully shall dwell in torments.
[10]For such as in their life have received benefits, and have not known me;
[11]And they that have loathed my law, while they had yet liberty, and, when as yet place of repentance was open unto them, understood not, but despised it;
[12]The same must know it after death by pain.

snippet.textDisplay: Diversity is amazing but only when it makes sense. In all actuality it ALMOST makes sense. In 11th century Norway,  Eric the Red had a "blaumen"(Norwegian for black skinned) steward named Thorhall. Vikings captured Moors from Spain and kept them as captives and slaves/stewards. I think people forget that Africa had an empire in Europe, bringing them out of the dark ages. Then after the empire's collapse many Moors remained in Europe. Ireland had a notable black family. Many in southern Ireland have African ancestry to this day and are referred to as "Black Irish". In England there was a queen of moorish descent. Now his high position in the military doesn't make any sense or his dark skin. After that many centuries the black would have been bred out by then in Norway as is what happened in most of Europe. Not many options for maintaining that dark of a skin tone. So yeah due to the time period being after the age of Vikings, after the fall of the Moorish empire and so far north in Norway where there is very little sunshine....no its not possible to have a dark skinned black man in that high of a position in power. Now France... in that time period, the father of Alexander Dumas was a great general that drove Napoleon insane with jealousy causing him to frame and imprison General Thomas-Alexandre Dumas, inspiring his son's "Man in the Iron Mask" novel. He also inspired the 3 musketeers. That was revolutionary France in the late 1700s early 1800s. Ignorance is the leading cause of racism. People have literally no idea how prominent & amazing black history is. Most people assume that Africans were savages rolling around in the mud when it was Europe in the mud when Africa brought modern civilization to it. So perhaps seeing as how a dark skinned African general existed in France at that time period (Mattias was probably inspired by Dumas) it is possible. If you look at old pictures of people in countries that you wouldn't expect to have black people...there were black people. Like China. Black has been getting bred out. Purposely in many cases. Ask Australia

snippet.textDisplay:
It's funny, and Kate McKinnon is a national treasure. I do have to nitpick one thing: the existence of Mattias in rural Norway in 1840. The short version: it's actually quite believable. There were many people of African descent in Europe during the 19th century (and before). Read on for the long version.

Norway was effectively part of Sweden from 1814-1905, and had been ruled by Denmark for the 400 years prior to that. Under both of those nations, it was part of the transatlantic slave trade and slavery in the Scandinavian countries wasn't abolished until 1847. Most, but not all, of the Africans enslaved and transported by those nations went to colonies in the Caribbean. Some ended up in Scandinavia.

One of the few we have an extensive record of was named Hans Jonathan. He was taken by his owners to Copenhagen when he was 7 years old and later fought in the Danish navy during the Napoleonic Wars (Denmark-Norway's French and Ottoman allies also had soldiers and sailors of African and Middle Eastern descent ... Thomas-Alexandre Dumas was even a general). After being declared free by the crown prince, his former masters won a court case to keep ownership of Hans Jonathan. Rather than be sent back to the Virgin Islands to be sold, he escaped to Iceland where he started a family and seems to have gotten something close to a "happily ever after" as the first Black Icelander until his death in 1827. At least 780 modern Icelanders are descended from him. You can read more about him in the book, "The Man Who Stole Himself" by Gisli Palsson.

If a small, independent city state like Arendelle with no economic interest in slavery had existed, it's actually quite likely it would have attracted escaped slaves freeing themselves, some even with military experience.
